Create a query that fetches student_name, course_id, student_id and grade in one table. Order the result by grade in ascending order.

Select students.name AS student_name,
course_id, 
student_id, 
grade
From grades
Join students ON grades.student_id = students.id
Order by grade

Calculate for each student their average grade and return the name and the average grade for each.
Name the columns student, grade.
Round the average to 2 decimal places and sort the result by the average grade in ascending order.

Select students.name AS student, ROUND(AVG(grades.grade),2) AS grade
From grades
Join students ON grades.student_id = students.id
Group by student
Order by grade ASC;

Find the customer IDs of customers who have ordered products with a unit price less than 10, and list the total quantity of those cheap products each customer has ordered.
Return following columns:
customer_id
total_quantity (the sum of quantities of products with a unit price < 10 for each customer)
SELECT 
    orders.customer_id,
    SUM(order_items.quantity) AS total_quantity
FROM orders
JOIN order_items ON orders.id = order_items.order_id
JOIN products ON order_items.product_id = products.id
WHERE products.unit_price < 10
GROUP BY orders.customer_id
ORDER BY orders.customer_id;

_______________________________________ Self Joins ______________________________________

Find pairs of friends who are mutual friends (mutual friendship exists when person A's friend_id points to person B AND person B's friend_id points to person A). Display both friends names in a single row. Name the columns friend1 and friend2.
Note: Include in the WHERE clause the criteria friend1.id < friend2.id so that it will not include duplicate pairs

Select friend1.name as friend1, friend2.name as friend2
From friends as friend1
JOIN friends as friend2 
on friend1.friend_id = friend2.id -- Checks mutual relationship
AND friend2.friend_id = friend1.id
WHERE friend1.id < friend2.id -- helps prevent duplicates

For each person in the friends table, find all the friend-of-friend connections they have. A friend-of-friend connection occurs when person A is friends with person B, who is in turn friends with person C. List these connections as three columns:
friend1: the starting person
friend2: their direct friend
friend3: their friend's friend
Rules:
Don't include cases where friend3 is the same person as friend1
Order the results by friend1's name in descending order
Example: If Alice is friends with Bob, and Bob is friends with Carol, then Alice-Bob-Carol would be a valid friend-of-friend connection.

Select friend1.name AS friend1,
friend2.name AS friend2,
friend3.name AS friend3
From friends AS friend1
Join friends AS friend2
ON friend1.friend_id = friend2.id
Join friends AS friend3
ON friend2.friend_id = friend3.id
AND friend2.friend_id = friend3.id
Where friend3.id != friend1.id
Order By friend1.name DESC

WITH date_comparisons AS (
    -- Step 1: Compare every pair of dates for each asset
    SELECT 
        r1.asset_id,
        r1.value AS newer_value,
        r2.value AS older_value,
        r1.date AS newer_date,
        r2.date AS older_date,
        (r1.value * 1.0 / r2.value) AS growth_ratio,
        (julianday(r1.date) - julianday(r2.date)) AS day_difference
    FROM real_estate r1
    JOIN real_estate r2 
        ON r1.asset_id = r2.asset_id
        AND r1.date > r2.date  -- Ensure r1 is newer than r2
    WHERE (julianday(r1.date) - julianday(r2.date)) >= 101  -- Only keep differences >= 101 days
),
max_ratios AS (
    -- Step 2: Keep only the biggest ratio for each asset
    SELECT 
        asset_id,
        MAX(growth_ratio) AS max_growth_ratio
    FROM date_comparisons
    GROUP BY asset_id
)
-- Step 3: Join with potential table and calculate ratio_forecast
SELECT 
    mr.asset_id,
    (mr.max_growth_ratio * 1.0 / p.forecast) AS ratio_forecast
FROM max_ratios mr
JOIN potential p ON mr.asset_id = p.asset_id
WHERE (mr.max_growth_ratio * 1.0 / p.forecast) > 1
ORDER BY ratio_forecast DESC;
